  <!-- Why Direct Vision -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-ivory">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-serif text-primary-900 mb-8">Why Direct Vision? The Logic</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-warmGray">
        <p class="mb-6">
          Endoscopic facial surgery was developed to provide visualization in deep spaces without
          large incisions. The camera allows the surgeon to see areas they couldn't otherwise access
          visually.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">But endoscopes come with significant trade-offs:</p>

        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
          <li><strong>Equipment cost:</strong> $100,000-$150,000 for a proper tower setup</li>
          <li><strong>Equipment dependency:</strong> Malfunction = compromised procedure</li>
          <li><strong>Learning curve:</strong> Hand-eye coordination with camera view</li>
          <li><strong>2D limitation:</strong> Loss of stereoscopic (3D) vision</li>
          <li><strong>Camera delay:</strong> Slight lag between movement and display</li>
          <li>
            <strong>No tactile feedback:</strong> You feel less through instruments designed for camera
            work
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="mb-6">
          Dr. Brandão's insight was simple: <strong
            >if you can achieve equivalent or better visualization without the camera, the
            trade-offs aren't worth it.</strong
          >
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          With proper incision placement in ENDOMIDFACE®, the temporal incision provides direct
          line-of-sight to the subperiosteal plane of the midface. Surgical loupes provide
          magnification. A headlight provides illumination. You see directly, in 3D, with zero
          delay, and with full tactile feedback preserved.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          The <a
            href="/creator/case-series-safety"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline"
            >safety record of 1,500+ surgeries with zero permanent nerve injuries</a
          > validates that Direct Vision doesn't compromise outcomes — it may actually enhance them.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6">
          For a detailed comparison, see: <a
            href="/methods/endomidface/direct-vision-vs-endoscopic"
            class="text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 underline"
            >Direct Vision vs Endoscopic Tower: Myth vs Reality</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ideal Patient -->
